</caption>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1711,2036]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[196,330,1711,1737]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">Pronotum.</emphasis>
Broader than head (
<figureCitation box="[569,640,1712,1738]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,255,1751,1775]" captionTargetBox="[197,1402,815,1731]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[197,1402,814,1731]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Habitus of H. perijaensis sp. n.. A) dorsal; B) ventral; C) lateral. Scale bar = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/275691/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">
Figs 
<number box="[629,640,1712,1738]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
A– 
<number box="[684,695,1712,1738]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" value="1.0">1</number>
B, 
<number box="[728,743,1712,1738]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" value="2.0">2</number>
A), widest at hind angles, nearly as wide as elytra; anterior margin excavated to receive head; lateral margins arcuate, sides deeply explanate, posterior margin arcuate, distance between hind angles twice the length of pronotum anterior to hind margins medially. Prosternum short, spinasternum depressed, obscure. Procoxal cavities opened posteriorly, procoxae conical, prominent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1711,2036]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,376,1861,1887]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">Mesosternum.</emphasis>
Short, mesocoxal cavities widely separated, mesocoxae small, ovate; mesosternal disc wider than long, separating mesocoxae (
<figureCitation box="[623,701,1898,1924]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,255,1751,1775]" captionTargetBox="[197,1402,815,1731]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[197,1402,814,1731]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Habitus of H. perijaensis sp. n.. A) dorsal; B) ventral; C) lateral. Scale bar = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/275691/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">
Figs. 
<number box="[689,701,1898,1924]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
B, 
<number box="[738,753,1898,1924]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" value="3.0">3</number>
C).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1711,2036]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">
Metaventrite long (
<figureCitation box="[425,497,1936,1962]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,255,1751,1775]" captionTargetBox="[197,1402,815,1731]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[197,1402,814,1731]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Habitus of H. perijaensis sp. n.. A) dorsal; B) ventral; C) lateral. Scale bar = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/275691/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">
Figs 
<number box="[485,497,1936,1962]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
B, 
<number box="[536,551,1936,1962]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" value="3.0">3</number>
C), widest at hind angles, metacoxal cavities widely separated, metacoxae transverse, posteriorly enlarged and forming a coxal plate partially covering hind femora. Trochanters small, triangular. Femora and tibiae normal.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,1298]" box="[196,744,151,178]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[196,329,151,177]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">Scutellum.</emphasis>
Acute posteriorly, wider than long.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,1298]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[196,283,189,215]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">Elytra.</emphasis>
Truncate, exposing abdominal tergites, elytron longer (
<quantity box="[941,1050,189,215]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="54" unit="mm" value="0.6">0.60 mm</quantity>
) than wide (
<quantity box="[1197,1309,189,215]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.7" pageId="5" pageNumber="54" unit="mm" value="0.37">0.37 mm</quantity>
), widest at anterior half; setae moderately flat, setal length two-three times distance between elytral punctures (
<figureCitation box="[1332,1403,226,252]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,255,1751,1775]" captionTargetBox="[197,1402,815,1731]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[197,1402,814,1731]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Habitus of H. perijaensis sp. n.. A) dorsal; B) ventral; C) lateral. Scale bar = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/275691/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">
Figs 
<number box="[1392,1403,226,252]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
A, 
<number box="[151,166,264,290]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54" value="2.0">2</number>
B– 
<number box="[203,218,264,290]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54" value="2.0">2</number>
C).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,1298]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[196,351,301,327]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">
<collectingCountry box="[196,261,301,327]" name="India" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">Hind</collectingCountry>
wings.
</emphasis>
Present, fringe of setae along margin of wing membrane, setae longest (
<quantity box="[1240,1353,301,327]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" pageId="5" pageNumber="54" unit="mm" value="0.22">0.22 mm</quantity>
) along distal margin of wing, width of wing membrane widest (
<quantity box="[811,919,338,364]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.1" pageId="5" pageNumber="54" unit="mm" value="0.41">0.41 mm</quantity>
) distally.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,1298]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[196,267,375,401]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">Tarsi.</emphasis>
<number box="[278,292,376,402]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54" value="3.0">3</number>
– 
<number box="[311,325,376,402]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54" value="3.0">3</number>
– 
<number box="[343,357,376,402]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54" value="3.0">3</number>
; claws moderate, wider at base than distally, males possessing an oblong disc at base of protarsal claws; meso- and metatarsal claws of male subequal, the outer claw possessing an invagination medially, anterioly to base of claw.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,1298]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[196,329,487,513]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">Abdomen.</emphasis>
Narrowed posteriorly, possessing a dense mat of recumbent setae on tergite IV, forming a plastron beneath elytra; tergite VIII of female rounded apically (
<figureCitation box="[976,1053,525,551]" captionStart="FIGURE 5. H" captionStartId="4.[151,258,1615,1639]" captionTargetBox="[171,1398,198,1614]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,176,1614]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 5. H. perijaensis sp. n. A) tergite VIII, female; B) sternite VIII, male; C) terminal abdominal segments, female; D) terminal abdominal segments, male; E) aedeagus (lateral)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/275695/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">
Fig. 
<number box="[1037,1053,525,551]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
A), terminal segments tapered posteriorly, acute, bifid (
<figureCitation box="[469,546,562,588]" captionStart="FIGURE 5. H" captionStartId="4.[151,258,1615,1639]" captionTargetBox="[171,1398,198,1614]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,176,1614]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 5. H. perijaensis sp. n. A) tergite VIII, female; B) sternite VIII, male; C) terminal abdominal segments, female; D) terminal abdominal segments, male; E) aedeagus (lateral)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/275695/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">
Fig. 
<number box="[530,546,562,588]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
C); abdominal sternite VIII of male possessing two widely separated, moderately acute lobes along posterior margin (
<figureCitation box="[707,776,600,626]" captionStart="FIGURE 5. H" captionStartId="4.[151,258,1615,1639]" captionTargetBox="[171,1398,198,1614]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,176,1614]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 5. H. perijaensis sp. n. A) tergite VIII, female; B) sternite VIII, male; C) terminal abdominal segments, female; D) terminal abdominal segments, male; E) aedeagus (lateral)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/275695/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">
Fig. 
<number box="[761,776,600,626]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
B), sternite IX not tapered, hind margin arcuate medially with hind angles widely separated (
<figureCitation box="[572,643,637,663]" captionStart="FIGURE 5. H" captionStartId="4.[151,258,1615,1639]" captionTargetBox="[171,1398,198,1614]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,176,1614]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 5. H. perijaensis sp. n. A) tergite VIII, female; B) sternite VIII, male; C) terminal abdominal segments, female; D) terminal abdominal segments, male; E) aedeagus (lateral)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/275695/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">
Fig. 
<number box="[628,643,637,663]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
D). Aedeagus 
<quantity box="[813,919,637,663]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="54" unit="mm" value="0.3">0.30 mm</quantity>
long, acute posteriorly, widest anteriorly at basal bulb (
<figureCitation box="[286,356,674,700]" captionStart="FIGURE 5. H" captionStartId="4.[151,258,1615,1639]" captionTargetBox="[171,1398,198,1614]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,176,1614]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 5. H. perijaensis sp. n. A) tergite VIII, female; B) sternite VIII, male; C) terminal abdominal segments, female; D) terminal abdominal segments, male; E) aedeagus (lateral)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/275695/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">
Fig. 
<number box="[341,356,674,700]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
E).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="54" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,1298]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[196,356,711,737]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">Distribution.</emphasis>
Currently known from two sites located less than 
<quantity box="[950,1009,712,738]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="54" unit="km" value="1.0">1 km</quantity>
apart in the foothills of the Serrania de Perija near Toromo, along the northwestern border of 
<collectingCountry box="[817,941,749,775]" name="Venezuela" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="54" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,1298]" box="[196,963,786,812]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[196,337,786,812]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is derived from the 
<typeStatus box="[812,862,786,812]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">type</typeStatus>
locality.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,1298]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[196,326,823,849]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">Bionomics</emphasis>
. The species was first encountered in the wet season (September) living in a seepage flowing over exposed, sunlit rock adjacent to a small stream (
<figureCitation box="[772,844,861,887]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="6.[151,256,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,264,1883]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,264,1884]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 6. Type locality of H. perijaensis sp. n., Venezuela: Zulia State, edge of Perija National Park at Toromo. A) Seepage habitat at type locality on 23 September 2007 (wet season); B) overview of the type locality on 28 January 2009 (dry season), and C) 23 September 2007." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/275696/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">
Fig. 
<number box="[827,844,861,887]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
). The same site was visited in the early dry season (January) at which time the seepages were completely dry. However, the small stream was now reduced to a small trickle with areas mimicking the now-dry side seepage in which many specimens of the new species were found, particularly in clumps of moss. The species was also found in a similar exposed seepage habitat in a second stream less than 
<quantity box="[507,570,1010,1036]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="54" unit="km" value="1.0">1 km</quantity>
west of the first site. No specimens were found in other co-occurring habitats such as sandy stream margins or leaf packs. Over the last several years a number of Venezuelan rock seepage habitats have been examined by 
<collectionCode box="[659,735,1085,1111]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">AEZS</collectionCode>
and several Venezuelan colleagues including sites in the primary Venezuelan Andes, the Cordillera de la Costa, and in 
<collectingCountry box="[908,995,1122,1148]" name="Guyana" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">Guiana</collectingCountry>
Shield-associated outcrops. Despite these efforts no other 
<taxonomicName box="[405,562,1160,1185]" class="Insecta" family="Hydroscaphidae" genus="Hydroscapha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[405,562,1160,1185]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">Hydroscapha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens have yet been found, suggesting the genus is not widespread or at least highly localized in distribution.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,1298]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">Numerous females were found to contain one to two nearly-fully developed eggs in specimens collected in the wet season (dry season specimens were not examined for this purpose).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
